HashTable in Java
`Hashtable` is a class in `java.util` that implements Map, Cloneable, and Serializable.
It is one of the oldest implementations of the Map interface in Java, predating `HashMap`.
Key Characteristics
- Stores key-value pairs.
- No null keys or null values allowed (unlike `HashMap`).
- Keys are unique.
- Thread-safe because all methods are synchronized.
- Generally slower than `HashMap` in single-threaded contexts due to synchronization overhead.
Categorized Methods
1. Adding / Updating Elements
●	`put(K key, V value)` – Associates value with key.
●	`putAll(Map m)` – Copies all mappings from another map.
2. Accessing Elements
●	`get(Object key)` – Returns value for key.
●	`getOrDefault(Object key, V defaultValue)` – Returns value or default if key not found.
3. Removing Elements
●	`remove(Object key)` – Removes mapping for key.
●	`remove(Object key, Object value)` – Removes entry only if key maps to given value.
●	`clear()` – Removes all mappings.
4. Searching & Checking
●	`containsKey(Object key)` – Checks if key exists.
●	`contains(Object value)` – Checks if value exists.
●	`containsValue(Object value)` – Checks if value exists.
●	`isEmpty()` – Checks if empty.
●	`size()` – Returns number of mappings.
●	`equals(Object o)` – Compares with another map.
●	`hashCode()` – Returns hash code.
5. Iteration Methods
●	`keys()` – Returns enumeration of keys.
●	`elements()` – Returns enumeration of values.
●	`entrySet()` – Returns set of key-value pairs.
●	`keySet()` – Returns set of keys.
●	`values()` – Returns collection of values.
●	`forEach(BiConsumer action)` – Performs action for each entry.
6. Legacy Methods
●	`contains(Object value)` – Legacy synonym for `containsValue()`.
7. Cloning
●	`clone()` – Creates shallow copy.
Java Code Demonstration

import java.util.*;

public class HashTableDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Hashtable<Integer, String> table = new Hashtable<>();

        // 1. Adding / Updating Elements
        table.put(1, "A");
        table.put(2, "B");
        table.put(3, "C");
        table.putAll(Map.of(4, "D", 5, "E"));

        // 2. Accessing Elements
        System.out.println(table.get(2));
        System.out.println(table.getOrDefault(10, "Not Found"));

        // 3. Removing Elements
        table.remove(3);
        table.remove(4, "D");

        // 4. Searching & Checking
        System.out.println(table.containsKey(1));
        System.out.println(table.contains("B")); // legacy method
        System.out.println(table.containsValue("E"));
        System.out.println(table.isEmpty());
        System.out.println(table.size());
        System.out.println(table.equals(Map.of(1, "A", 2, "B", 5, "E")));
        System.out.println(table.hashCode());

        // 5. Iteration
        Enumeration<Integer> keys = table.keys();
        while (keys.hasMoreElements()) {
            System.out.println("Key: " + keys.nextElement());
        }

        Enumeration<String> values = table.elements();
        while (values.hasMoreElements()) {
            System.out.println("Value: " + values.nextElement());
        }

        for (Map.Entry<Integer, String> entry : table.entrySet()) {
            System.out.println("Entry: " + entry.getKey() + " -> " + entry.getValue());
        }

        table.forEach((k, v) -> System.out.println(k + " = " + v));

        // 6. Cloning
        Hashtable<Integer, String> cloned = (Hashtable<Integer, String>) table.clone();
        System.out.println("Cloned Hashtable: " + cloned);
    }
}

